First, we draw line $CG$. Notice that $\angle CBG$ consists of a $60^\circ$ angle and a $90^\circ$ angle, hence, $\angle CBG = 150^\circ$.

Since $CB=BG$, $\triangle CBG$ is isosceles, with $\angle BCG= (1/2)(180^\circ - 150^\circ) = 15^\circ$.

Finally, to find $\angle GCE$, we subtract $\angle BCG$ from $\angle BCE$ (which measures $60^\circ$ as it is an angle of the triangle.)

Hence our desired answer is $\angle GCE = 60^\circ - 15^\circ = \boxed{45^\circ}$.

