\[\arctan 1 + \arctan \frac{1}{2} + \arctan \frac{1}{3} = \frac{\pi}{4} + \frac{\pi}{4} = \boxed{\frac{\pi}{2}}.\]

To perform division in complex numbers, we multiply both the numerator and the denominator by the conjugate of the denominator. In this case, the conjugate of $1+2i$ is $1-2i$. Multiplying: \begin{align*}
\frac{-3+4i}{1+2i}&=\frac{(-3+4i)(1-2i)}{(1+2i)(1-2i)}\\
&=\frac{-3+4i+6i-8i^2}{1+2i-2i-4i^2}\\
&=\frac{5+10i}{5}\\
&=\boxed{1+2i}
\end{align*}

Cross multiplying, we obtain $ x+1 = 2(3x-1)$. (This is the same thing as multiplying both sides by both $3x-1$ and by $x+1$.)  Then, we solve for $x$: \begin{align*}
x+1 &= 2(3x-1)\\
\Rightarrow \qquad x+1 &= 6x-2\\
\Rightarrow \qquad-5x &= -3\\
\Rightarrow \qquad x &= \boxed{\frac{3}{5}}.
